      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling an Off-the-Plan Property Before Completion in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Contract assignment allows some off-the-plan purchasers to sell their position before the building completes. The rules in Queensland are specific, and the financial consequences of getting it wrong are significant.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Off-the-plan purchases are common in Brisbane, particularly in inner-city apartments and townhouse developments where buyers commit to a contract before construction is complete. Circumstances change during the build period, which can last anywhere from twelve months to three years or more. People relocate, financial situations shift, or a buyer who purchased speculatively decides they no longer want to settle. The question of what to do with an off-the-plan contract before the building completes depends almost entirely on what the contract itself says.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What an assignment of contract is and how it works</h2>
      <p>Assigning a contract means transferring your position as the buyer to a new party before settlement. The original buyer (the assignor) steps out of the contract, and the new buyer (the assignee) steps in and takes on all the rights and obligations of the original purchaser from that point forward. The original off-the-plan contract between the developer and the original purchaser remains in place; it simply has a different buyer attached to it.</p>

      <p>This is different from a standard property resale. In a standard resale, the original buyer settles, takes title to the property, and then sells it as a completed asset. An assignment occurs before settlement, so the property never formally passes through the assignor's hands. The assignee settles directly with the developer and receives title.</p>

      <p>The key document is the deed of assignment, which records the transfer of contractual rights and obligations from the original purchaser to the new purchaser. This needs to be prepared by a solicitor and executed correctly. The developer's consent is also typically required, and how straightforward or difficult that consent is to obtain depends on the developer and the contract terms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When developers allow assignments and when they do not</h2>
      <p>Whether you can assign your off-the-plan contract depends on the specific terms of that contract. Many off-the-plan contracts in Queensland include a clause permitting assignment with the developer's consent, which the developer agrees not to unreasonably withhold. In practice, this means you need to formally request the developer's consent and provide details of the proposed assignee. The developer will typically charge an assignment fee, which is commonly between $1,000 and $5,000 depending on the development, though some are higher.</p>

      <p>Some contracts contain absolute restrictions on assignment, meaning the original buyer cannot transfer the contract under any circumstances before settlement. These clauses are legal and enforceable in Queensland. Attempting to assign a contract in breach of this clause creates serious legal exposure, including potential forfeiture of the deposit.</p>

      <p>A third category of contract permits assignment subject to conditions, such as requiring the assignee to demonstrate equivalent financial capacity to the original purchaser, or restricting assignment to parties who are not competitors of the developer. Reading the specific assignment clause in your contract is the critical first step. This is not something to approach without legal advice.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tax implications of assigning versus settling and reselling</h2>
      <p>The tax consequences of assigning an off-the-plan contract differ significantly from those of settling and then reselling, and the difference matters enough that it should inform your decision about which path to take.</p>

      <p>When you assign a contract, you are selling a contractual right, not a property. The gain, if any, is the difference between what you paid under the original contract (plus any assignment costs) and the amount the assignee pays you. This gain is generally treated as income from the disposal of an asset and is subject to Capital Gains Tax. If you have held the contractual interest for more than twelve months, you may be eligible for the 50% CGT discount on the gain, though this depends on your individual circumstances and you should confirm with a tax adviser.</p>

      <p>An important point specific to Queensland: stamp duty (transfer duty) is payable by the assignee on the assignment transaction. The assignee also pays duty again on the final settlement with the developer in some circumstances. This double duty exposure can make an assigned contract less attractive to buyers than a completed resale, which affects pricing and the pool of buyers willing to take an assignment.</p>

      <p>If you settle and then resell as a completed property, the tax treatment is more straightforward: you pay CGT on the difference between your purchase price (including all acquisition costs) and your sale price (net of selling costs). The 50% discount applies if you hold the property for more than twelve months. The tradeoff is the settlement costs, including the remaining balance of the purchase price, stamp duty on the completed property, and the holding costs during the period between settlement and resale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to market an assignable contract</h2>
      <p>Marketing an off-the-plan contract assignment is different from marketing a completed property. The buyer pool is narrower: you are looking for someone willing to take on a contract for a property they cannot physically inspect in its completed state, often in a market where equivalent completed properties may be available.</p>

      <p>The appeal to prospective assignees is typically price. If the property has increased in value since the original contract was signed, the assignee is effectively buying in at the original contract price (plus the assignment premium) rather than the current market value. This can be a meaningful discount in a rising market, which is the primary reason buyers accept the additional complexity and stamp duty exposure.</p>

      <p>Working with a real estate agent who has experience in off-the-plan assignments is important. Not all agents understand the process or have the buyer connections to find suitable assignees. The documentation requirements are more complex than a standard sale, and the agent needs to be comfortable working alongside your solicitor throughout the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer due diligence on off-the-plan assignments</h2>
      <p>From the assignee's perspective, buying into an off-the-plan assignment requires careful due diligence. The assignee is taking on all the obligations of the original contract, which means they need to understand exactly what those obligations are. This includes the purchase price, the deposit arrangement, the sunset clause (the date by which the development must complete or the buyer can terminate), any special conditions, and the developer's track record for delivery.</p>

      <p>The assignee should have their own solicitor review the original contract and the deed of assignment before committing. They should also conduct their own research into the developer's financial position and the progress of construction. A development that is behind schedule or where the developer is under financial pressure creates risk for the assignee that was not present for the original buyer at the time of purchase.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The risks for both assignor and assignee</h2>
      <p>For the assignor, the main risks are completing the assignment in breach of contract (potentially losing the deposit), failing to get proper tax advice and facing an unexpected liability, and accepting a price for the assignment that is less than the net return from settling and reselling as a completed property.</p>

      <p>For the assignee, the main risks are the double stamp duty exposure noted above, inheriting a contract with conditions or complications that were not fully disclosed, and the development not completing as expected. The sunset clause is particularly important: if the development does not complete by the sunset date, the assignee typically has the right to terminate and recover the deposit, but this outcome is disruptive and the delay can be costly if the assignee had made plans around the anticipated settlement date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When settling first makes more financial sense</h2>
      <p>In many cases, settling and then reselling the completed property is a cleaner and more financially sound outcome than attempting an assignment. The buyer pool for a completed, titled property is vastly larger than the pool for a contract assignment. Buyers can physically inspect the property, their finance approval is more straightforward, and the stamp duty exposure is a single, predictable amount.</p>

      <p>If the assignment premium you could achieve is modest relative to the development's appreciation since your purchase date, the additional complexity of the assignment process may not be worth it. Running the numbers on both scenarios with your accountant and solicitor before committing to an assignment is the only way to make this judgment with confidence.</p>

      <p>The calculation also depends on how close the development is to completion. An assignment twelve months before expected completion is a different proposition from an assignment two months out. The nearer to settlement, the harder it is to find a willing assignee and the less the time savings are worth to them.</p>

